{
  "answer": "In the Urdu corpus, *rind* (رند, plural *rindān*)—often rendered in English translation as \"sinner,\" \"libertine,\" or \"mystic drunkard\"—is a Sufi poetic archetype denoting an outwardly irreverent, wine-loving figure whose apparent libertinism masks profound spiritual intoxication and union with the Divine.[^1][^2] It contrasts sharply with the *zahīd* (pious ascetic or cleric), who clings to rigid legalism (*zuhd*) at the expense of ecstatic love (*ʿishq*). The term evokes the tavern (*maikhāna*) as a metaphor for divine presence, where the rind transcends Sharia's externals through inner gnosis (*maʿrifa*).\n\nTheologically, *rind* performs critical work in Sufi-inspired Urdu poetry by subverting pharisaical piety: it posits that true devotion integrates worldly \"sin\" (e.g., music, beauty, wine as divine symbols) with sacred law, embodying a holistic Islam where the heart's freedom (*rindi*) reveals God's mercy beyond judgment.[^3] Allama Iqbal elevates the rind as a model for the modern Muslim self—self-aware yet paradoxical, like Mansur al-Hallaj—against the cleric's hypocrisy.[^4] Ghalib similarly valorizes the *rindān* as spiritually essential companions, preferable to overly cautious mystics.[^5]\n\nThis motif dominates Iqbal's *Bang-e-Dara Part 1* but recurs in classical ghazals; the corpus lacks systematic prose theology on it (no dedicated treatises found).\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/44-zuhd-aur-rindi/translation/#p-34574a).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/06-kushaada-dast-e-karam-jab-woh-beniyaaz-kare/translation/#p-d3d598).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/44-zuhd-aur-rindi/translation/#p-ea39dc).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [full chapter](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/44-zuhd-aur-rindi/translation/).\n\n[^5]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/22-chahiye-achhon-ko-jitna-chahiye/translation/#p-c886a3).",
